{
  "doc_id": "54059",
  "text": "EPA and DHA exhibit not only anti-inflammatory properties, but also help to restore the homeostasis of tissues after inflammation: some of their metabolites are considered specialized pro-resolving mediators [CITATION_1] . From this point of view, the metabolism of EPA can lead to the formation of Resolvin E (RvE) series and the metabolism of DHA can lead to the formation of Resolvin D (RvD) series, maresins, and protectins, which are able to stimulate resolution mechanisms of inflammation [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . RvE1, RvD1, and protectin D1 are able to prevent transendothelial migration of neutrophils; RvD1 and protectin D1 can inhibit IL-1β production; protectin D1 also inhibits TNF-α production [CITATION_7] .",
